### Description

Consider the following code:

```ts
@Component({
  //...
  template: `
    <!-- not doing the correct !isFalsy() check -->
    @if (!isFalsy) {
      Hello world!
    }
  `,
  //...
})
export class ExampleComponent {
  isFalsy = signal<boolean>(true);
}
```

This code compiles without giving any errors/warnings, and while it obviously would be normal to, testing for falsy against the signal functions *should* be a mistake unless there are some legit use cases I'm unaware of.

### Proposed solution

Either error or give a warning saying that what you are doing might be a mistake when this happens.

### Alternatives considered

Couldn't think of other alternatives, but anything to help point these out in our code is a welcome change.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

When a component uses @ContentChild or @ContentChildren should is able to access the content elements by queries and interact with the directive/component instance.

The same **should work also** when the child component is created dynamic.


Assuming you have the following host:

_Host Component_
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <h1> Classic projection </h1>
    <app-parent>
      <app-child></app-child>
    </app-parent>
    <h1>Dynamic</h1>
    <app-parent>
      <ng-container #host></ng-container>
    </app-parent>
  `,
})
export class AppComponent implements AfterViewInit{
  title = 'testProjection';

  @ViewChild('host', {static: true, read: ViewContainerRef}) host!: ViewContainerRef;

  ngAfterViewInit(): void {
    this.host.createComponent(ChildComponent)
  }
}
```
And a parent component querying the childrens:

_Parent Component_
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-parent',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule],
  template: `<ng-content></ng-content>`,
})
export class ParentComponent implements AfterContentInit{

  @ContentChild(ChildComponent) child?: ChildComponent;

  @ContentChildren(ChildComponent) children?: QueryList<ChildComponent>;

  ngAfterContentInit(): void {
    console.log("child component", this.child);
    console.log("children component", this.children);
    this.children?.changes.subscribe(
      (children) => {
        console.log("children changed", children)
      }
    )
  }
}
```
And a child component injecting his parent

_Child Component_
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule],
  template: `<p>child works!</p>`,
})
export class ChildComponent {
  constructor(parent: ParentComponent) {
    console.log("parent component", parent);
  }
}
```

The "classic projection" example will work as intended, while the children created by the host component won't work inside the @Content queries.


The first example does resolve:
- @ContentChild
- @ContentChildren [1]
- parent injection trough construction of ChildComponent

The second example only resolve:
- parent injection trough construction of ChildComponent


Both the examples does render correctly, what is really missing is that any access to ChildComponent from the ParentComponent will not work in the dynamic case and breaks most of the compositions that does interacts with their content childrens.

_Rendered html_
```html
<app-root _nghost-owl-c2="" ng-version="15.2.10">
    <app-parent _ngcontent-owl-c2="">
        <app-child _ngcontent-owl-c2=""><p>child works!</p></app-child>
    </app-parent>
    <h1 _ngcontent-owl-c2="">Dynamic</h1>
    <app-parent _ngcontent-owl-c2="">
        <app-child><p>child works!</p></app-child><!--ng-container--></app-parent>
</app-root>
```


I dont know the internal limitations that makes this trivial example not working, but this r**eally hinders the capabilities of the framework** when it comes to dynamicly render components.

### Proposed solution

Allow content queries to resolve directives and components from content also when they are created dynamically but they match the same `ProviderToken`.


### Alternatives considered

The component may only uses `child -> parent` injection instead of content queries or use custom mechanism for handling queries.

Using `child -> parent` relationship can only be achived by design of the component's composition, so it won't necessarly works with all components from third parties (ex. Material).

Custom mechanism again can only be achived by design of the component's composition and also may not be optimal or implemented in consistent ways by library authors.


You can find the example in this stackblitz:
https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-zdzhrg?file=src%2Fmain.ts

